# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ternary-search-tree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] In computer science, a **binary search tree** (**BST**), also called an **ordered** or **sorted binary tree**, is a rooted binary tree data structure with the key of each internal node being greater than all the keys in the respective node's left subtree and less than the ones in its right subtree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The time complexity of operations on the binary search tree is linear with respect to the height of the tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees allow binary search for fast lookup, addition, and removal of data items.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Since the nodes in a BST are laid out so that each comparison skips about half of the remaining tree, the lookup performance is proportional to that of binary logarithm.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] BSTs were devised in the 1960s for the problem of efficient storage of labeled data and are attributed to Conway Berners-Lee and David Wheeler.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The performance of a binary search tree is dependent on the order of insertion of the nodes into the tree since arbitrary insertions may lead to degeneracy; several variations of the binary search tree can be built with guaranteed worst-case performance.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The basic operations include: search, traversal, insert and delete.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] BSTs with guaranteed worst-case complexities perform better than an unsorted array, which would require linear search time.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The complexity analysis of BST shows that, on average, the insert, delete and search takes $\Theta (\log n)$ for n nodes.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] In the worst case, they degrade to that of a singly linked list: $O(n)$ .
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] To address the boundless increase of the tree height with arbitrary insertions and deletions, self-balancing variants of BSTs are introduced to bound the worst lookup complexity to that of the binary logarithm.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] AVL trees were the first self-balancing binary search trees, invented in 1962 by Georgy Adelson-Velsky and Evgenii Landis.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees can be used to implement abstract data types such as dynamic sets, lookup tables and priority queues, and used in sorting algorithms such as tree sort.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The binary search tree algorithm was discovered independently by several researchers, including P.F.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Windley, Andrew Donald Booth, Andrew Colin, Thomas N.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The algorithm is attributed to Conway Berners-Lee and David Wheeler, who used it for storing labeled data in magnetic tapes in 1960.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] One of the earliest and popular binary search tree algorithm is that of Hibbard.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The time complexity of a binary search tree increases boundlessly with the tree height if the nodes are inserted in an arbitrary order, therefore self-balancing binary search trees were introduced to bound the height of the tree to $O(\log n)$ .
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Various **height-balanced** binary search trees were introduced to confine the tree height, such as AVL trees, Treaps, and red–black trees.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are also efficacious in sortings and search algorithms.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are also a fundamental data structure used in construction of abstract data structures such as sets, multisets, and associative arrays.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Searching in a binary search tree for a specific key can be programmed recursively or iteratively.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Searching begins by examining the root node.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] If the tree is nil, the key being searched for does not exist in the tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Otherwise, if the key equals that of the root, the search is successful and the node is returned.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] If the key is less than that of the root, the search proceeds by examining the left subtree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Similarly, if the key is greater than that of the root, the search proceeds by examining the right subtree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] This process is repeated until the key is found or the remaining subtree is ${\text{nil}}$ .
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] If the searched key is not found after a ${\text{nil}}$ subtree is reached, then the key is not present in the tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The following pseudocode implements the BST search procedure through recursion.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The recursive procedure continues until a ${\text{nil}}$ or the ${\text{key}}$ being searched for are encountered.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The recursive version of the search can be "unrolled" into a while loop.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] On most machines, the iterative version is found to be more efficient.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Since the search may proceed till some leaf node, the running time complexity of BST search is $O(h)$ where h is the height of the tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] However, the worst case for BST search is $O(n)$ where n is the total number of nodes in the BST, because an unbalanced BST may degenerate to a linked list.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] However, if the BST is height-balanced the height is $O(\log n)$ .
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] For certain operations, given a node ${\text{x}}$ , finding the successor or predecessor of ${\text{x}}$ is crucial.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Assuming all the keys of a BST are distinct, the successor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST is the node with the smallest key greater than ${\text{x}}$ 's key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] On the other hand, the predecessor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST is the node with the largest key smaller than ${\text{x}}$ 's key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The following pseudocode finds the successor and predecessor of a node ${\text{x}}$ in a BST.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Operations such as finding a node in a BST whose key is the maximum or minimum are critical in certain operations, such as determining the successor and predecessor of nodes.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Following is the pseudocode for the operations.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Operations such as insertion and deletion cause the BST representation to change dynamically.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The data structure must be modified in such a way that the properties of BST continue to hold.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] New nodes are inserted as leaf nodes in the BST.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Following is an iterative implementation of the insertion operation.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The procedure maintains a "trailing pointer" ${\text{y}}$ as a parent of ${\text{x}}$ .
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] After initialization on line 2, the **while** loop along lines 4-11 causes the pointers to be updated.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] If ${\text{y}}$ is ${\text{nil}}$ , the BST is empty, thus ${\text{z}}$ is inserted as the root node of the binary search tree ${\text{T}}$ , if it is not ${\text{nil}}$ , insertion proceeds by comparing the keys to that of ${\text{y}}$ on the lines 15-19 and the node is inserted accordingly.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] If ${\text{Z}}$ has only one child, the child node of ${\text{Z}}$ gets elevated by modifying the parent node of ${\text{Z}}$ to point to the child node, consequently taking ${\text{Z}}$ 's position in the tree, as shown in (b) and (c).
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] If ${\text{Y}}$ lies within ${\text{Z}}$ 's right subtree but is not ${\text{Z}}$ 's right child, as shown in (e), ${\text{Y}}$ first gets replaced by its own right child, and then it displaces ${\text{Z}}$ 's position in the tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Alternatively, the in-order predecessor can also be used.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The following pseudocode implements the deletion operation in a binary search tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The ${\text{BST-Delete}}$ procedure deals with the 3 special cases mentioned above.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Lines 2-3 deal with case 1; lines 4-5 deal with case 2 and lines 6-16 for case 3.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The helper function ${\text{Shift-Nodes}}$ is used within the deletion algorithm for the purpose of replacing the node ${\text{u}}$ with ${\text{v}}$ in the binary search tree ${\text{BST}}$ .
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] This procedure handles the deletion (and substitution) of ${\text{u}}$ from ${\text{BST}}$ .
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] A BST can be traversed through three basic algorithms: inorder, preorder, and postorder tree walks.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Following is a recursive implementation of the tree walks.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Without rebalancing, insertions or deletions in a binary search tree may lead to degeneration, resulting in a height n of the tree (where n is number of items in a tree), so that the lookup performance is deteriorated to that of a linear search.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Keeping the search tree balanced and height bounded by $O(\log n)$ is a key to the usefulness of the binary search tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] This can be achieved by "self-balancing" mechanisms during the updation operations to the tree designed to maintain the tree height to the binary logarithmic complexity.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] A tree is height-balanced if the heights of the left sub-tree and right sub-tree are guaranteed to be related by a constant factor.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] This property was introduced by the AVL tree and continued by the red–black tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The heights of all the nodes on the path from the root to the modified leaf node have to be observed and possibly corrected on every insert and delete operation to the tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] In a weight-balanced tree, the criterion of a balanced tree is the number of leaves of the subtrees.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The weights of the left and right subtrees differ at most by 1 .
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] However, the difference is bound by a ratio $\alpha$ of the weights, since a strong balance condition of 1 cannot be maintained with $O(\log n)$ rebalancing work during insert and delete operations.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] The $\alpha$ -weight-balanced trees gives an entire family of balance conditions, where each left and right subtrees have each at least a fraction of $\alpha$ of the total weight of the subtree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] There are several self-balanced binary search trees, including T-tree, treap, red-black tree, B-tree, 2–3 tree, and Splay tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are used in sorting algorithms such as tree sort, where all the elements are inserted at once and the tree is traversed at an in-order fashion.
[src:ternary-search-tree/binary-search-tree] Binary search trees are used in implementing priority queues, using the node's key as priorities.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] In computer science, a **radix tree** (also **radix trie** or **compact prefix tree** or **compressed trie**) is a data structure that represents a space-optimized trie (prefix tree) in which each node that is the only child is merged with its parent.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] The number of children of every internal node is at most the radix r of the radix tree, where r = 2x for some integer x ≥ 1.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Unlike regular trees, edges can be labeled with sequences of elements as well as single elements.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] This makes radix trees much more efficient for small sets (especially if the strings are long) and for sets of strings that share long prefixes.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Unlike regular trees (where whole keys are compared *en masse* from their beginning up to the point of inequality), the key at each node is compared chunk-of-bits by chunk-of-bits, where the quantity of bits in that chunk at that node is the radix r of the radix trie.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] When r is 2, the radix trie is binary (i.e., compare that node's 1-bit portion of the key), which minimizes sparseness at the expense of maximizing trie depth—i.e., maximizing up to conflation of nondiverging bit-strings in the key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] When r ≥ 4 is a power of 2, then the radix trie is an r-ary trie, which lessens the depth of the radix trie at the expense of potential sparseness.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] As an optimization, edge labels can be stored in constant size by using two pointers to a string (for the first and last elements).
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Note that although the examples in this article show strings as sequences of characters, the type of the string elements can be chosen arbitrarily; for example, as a bit or byte of the string representation when using multibyte character encodings or Unicode.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Radix trees are useful for constructing associative arrays with keys that can be expressed as strings.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] They find particular application in the area of IP routing, where the ability to contain large ranges of values with a few exceptions is particularly suited to the hierarchical organization of IP addresses.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] They are also used for inverted indexes of text documents in information retrieval.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Radix trees support insertion, deletion, and searching operations.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Insertion adds a new string to the trie while trying to minimize the amount of data stored.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Deletion removes a string from the trie.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Searching operations include (but are not necessarily limited to) exact lookup, find predecessor, find successor, and find all strings with a prefix.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] All of these operations are O(*k*) where k is the maximum length of all strings in the set, where length is measured in the quantity of bits equal to the radix of the radix trie.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] The lookup operation determines if a string exists in a trie.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Most operations modify this approach in some way to handle their specific tasks.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] For instance, the node where a string terminates may be of importance.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] This operation is similar to tries except that some edges consume multiple elements.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] The following pseudo code assumes that these methods and members exist.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] To insert a string, we search the tree until we can make no further progress.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] At this point we either add a new outgoing edge labeled with all remaining elements in the input string, or if there is already an outgoing edge sharing a prefix with the remaining input string, we split it into two edges (the first labeled with the common prefix) and proceed.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] This splitting step ensures that no node has more children than there are possible string elements.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Several cases of insertion are shown below.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] It is assumed that edges can be labelled with empty strings to terminate strings where necessary and that the root has no incoming edge.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] To delete a string x from a tree, we first locate the leaf representing x.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Then, assuming x exists, we remove the corresponding leaf node.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] If the parent of our leaf node has only one other child, then that child's incoming label is appended to the parent's incoming label and the child is removed.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] The data structure was invented in 1968 by Donald R.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Morrison, with whom it is primarily associated, and by Gernot Gwehenberger.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Donald Knuth, pages 498–500 in Volume III of The Art of Computer Programming, calls these "Patricia's trees", presumably after the acronym in the title of Morrison's paper: "PATRICIA - Practical Algorithm to Retrieve Information Coded in Alphanumeric".
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Today, Patricia trees are seen as radix trees with radix equals 2, which means that each bit of the key is compared individually and each node is a two-way (i.e., left versus right) branch.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Unlike balanced trees, radix trees permit lookup, insertion, and deletion in O(*k*) time rather than O(log *n*).
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] This does not seem like an advantage, since normally *k* ≥ log *n*, but in a balanced tree every comparison is a string comparison requiring O(*k*) worst-case time, many of which are slow in practice due to long common prefixes (in the case where comparisons begin at the start of the string).
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] In a trie, all comparisons require constant time, but it takes *m* comparisons to look up a string of length *m*.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Radix trees can perform these operations with fewer comparisons, and require many fewer nodes.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Radix trees also share the disadvantages of tries, however: as they can only be applied to strings of elements or elements with an efficiently reversible mapping to strings, they lack the full generality of balanced search trees, which apply to any data type with a total ordering.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] A reversible mapping to strings can be used to produce the required total ordering for balanced search trees, but not the other way around.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] This can also be problematic if a data type only provides a comparison operation, but not a (de)serialization operation.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Hash tables are commonly said to have expected O(1) insertion and deletion times, but this is only true when considering computation of the hash of the key to be a constant-time operation.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] When hashing the key is taken into account, hash tables have expected O(*k*) insertion and deletion times, but may take longer in the worst case depending on how collisions are handled.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Radix trees have worst-case O(*k*) insertion and deletion.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] The successor/predecessor operations of radix trees are also not implemented by hash tables.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] A common extension of radix trees uses two colors of nodes, "black" and "white".
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] To check if a given string is stored in the tree, the search starts from the top and follows the edges of the input string until no further progress can be made.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] If the search string is consumed and the final node is a black node, the search has failed; if it is white, the search has succeeded.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] This makes possible to add a large range of strings with a common prefix to the tree, using white nodes, then remove a small set of "exceptions" in a space-efficient manner by *inserting* them using black nodes.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] The **HAT-trie** is a cache-conscious data structure based on radix trees that offers efficient string storage and retrieval, and ordered iterations.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Performance, with respect to both time and space, is comparable to the cache-conscious hashtable.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] A **PATRICIA** trie is a special variant of the radix 2 (binary) trie, in which rather than explicitly store every bit of every key, the nodes store only the position of the first bit which differentiates two sub-trees.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] During traversal the algorithm examines the indexed bit of the search key and chooses the left or right sub-tree as appropriate.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Notable features of the PATRICIA trie include that the trie only requires one node to be inserted for every unique key stored, making PATRICIA much more compact than a standard binary trie.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Also, since the actual keys are no longer explicitly stored it is necessary to perform one full key comparison on the indexed record in order to confirm a match.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] In this respect PATRICIA bears a certain resemblance to indexing using a hash table.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] The **adaptive radix tree** is a radix tree variant that integrates adaptive node sizes to the radix tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] One major drawback of the usual radix trees is the use of space, because it uses a constant node size in every level.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] The major difference between the radix tree and the adaptive radix tree is its variable size for each node based on the number of child elements, which grows while adding new entries.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] Hence, the adaptive radix tree leads to a better use of space without reducing its speed.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] A common practice is to relax the criteria of disallowing parents with only one child in situations where the parent represents a valid key in the data set.
[src:ternary-search-tree/radix-tree] This variant of radix tree achieves a higher space efficiency than the one which only allows internal nodes with at least two children.
[src:ternary-search-tree/search-data-structure] In computer science, a **search data structure** is any data structure that allows the efficient retrieval of specific items from a set of items, such as a specific record from a database.
[src:ternary-search-tree/search-data-structure] The simplest, most general, and least efficient search structure is merely an unordered sequential list of all the items.
[src:ternary-search-tree/search-data-structure] Locating the desired item in such a list, by the linear search method, inevitably requires a number of operations proportional to the number *n* of items, in the worst case as well as in the average case.
[src:ternary-search-tree/search-data-structure] Useful search data structures allow faster retrieval; however, they are limited to queries of some specific kind.
[src:ternary-search-tree/search-data-structure] Moreover, since the cost of building such structures is at least proportional to *n*, they only pay off if several queries are to be performed on the same database (or on a database that changes little between queries).
[src:ternary-search-tree/search-data-structure] The simplest kind of query is to locate a record that has a specific field (the *key*) equal to a specified value *v*.
[src:ternary-search-tree/search-data-structure] Other common kinds of query are "find the item with smallest (or largest) key value", "find the item with largest key value not exceeding *v*", "find all items with key values between specified bounds *v*min and *v*max".
[src:ternary-search-tree/search-data-structure] In certain databases the key values may be points in some multi-dimensional space.
[src:ternary-search-tree/search-data-structure] For example, the key may be a geographic position (latitude and longitude) on the Earth.
[src:ternary-search-tree/search-data-structure] In that case, common kinds of queries are "find the record with a key closest to a given point *v*", or "find all items whose key lies at a given distance from *v*", or "find all items within a specified region *R* of the space".
[src:ternary-search-tree/search-data-structure] A common special case of the latter are simultaneous range queries on two or more simple keys, such as "find all employee records with salary between 50,000 and 100,000 and hired between 1995 and 2007".
[src:ternary-search-tree/search-data-structure] This table is only an approximate summary; for each data structure there are special situations and variants that may lead to different costs.
[src:ternary-search-tree/search-data-structure] Also two or more data structures can be combined to obtain lower costs.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] In computer science, a **suffix tree** (also called **PAT tree** or, in an earlier form, **position tree**) is a compressed trie containing all the suffixes of the given text as their keys and positions in the text as their values.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Suffix trees allow particularly fast implementations of many important string operations.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The construction of such a tree for the string S takes time and space linear in the length of S .
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Once constructed, several operations can be performed quickly, such as locating a substring in S , locating a substring if a certain number of mistakes are allowed, and locating matches for a regular expression pattern.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Suffix trees also provided one of the first linear-time solutions for the longest common substring problem.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] These speedups come at a cost: storing a string's suffix tree typically requires significantly more space than storing the string itself.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The concept was first introduced by Weiner (1973).
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Rather than the suffix $S[i..n]$ , Weiner stored in his trie the *prefix identifier* for each position, that is, the shortest string starting at i and occurring only once in S .
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] His *Algorithm D* takes an uncompressed trie for $S[k+1..n]$ and extends it into a trie for $S[k..n]$ .
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] This way, starting from the trivial trie for $S[n..n]$ , a trie for $S[1..n]$ can be built by $n-1$ successive calls to Algorithm D; however, the overall run time is $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Weiner's *Algorithm B* maintains several auxiliary data structures, to achieve an overall run time linear in the size of the constructed trie.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The latter can still be $O(n^{2})$ nodes, e.g. for $S=a^{n}b^{n}a^{n}b^{n}\$.$ Weiner's *Algorithm C* finally uses compressed tries to achieve linear overall storage size and run time.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Donald Knuth subsequently characterized the latter as "Algorithm of the Year 1973" according to his student Vaughan Pratt.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The text book Aho, Hopcroft & Ullman (1974, Sect.9.5) reproduced Weiner's results in a simplified and more elegant form, introducing the term *position tree*.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] McCreight (1976) was the first to build a (compressed) trie of all suffixes of S .
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Although the suffix starting at i is usually longer than the prefix identifier, their path representations in a compressed trie do not differ in size.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] On the other hand, McCreight could dispense with most of Weiner's auxiliary data structures; only suffix links remained.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Ukkonen (1995) further simplified the construction.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] He provided the first online-construction of suffix trees, now known as Ukkonen's algorithm, with running time that matched the then fastest algorithms.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] These algorithms are all linear-time for a constant-size alphabet, and have worst-case running time of $O(n\log n)$ in general.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Farach (1997) gave the first suffix tree construction algorithm that is optimal for all alphabets.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] In particular, this is the first linear-time algorithm for strings drawn from an alphabet of integers in a polynomial range.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Farach's algorithm has become the basis for new algorithms for constructing both suffix trees and suffix arrays, for example, in external memory, compressed, succinct, etc.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Except for the root, every internal node has at least two children.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Each edge is labelled with a non-empty substring of S .
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] No two edges starting out of a node can have string-labels beginning with the same character.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The string obtained by concatenating all the string-labels found on the path from the root to leaf i spells out suffix $S[i..n]$ , for i from 1 to n .
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] If a suffix of S is also the prefix of another suffix, such a tree does not exist for the string.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] For example, in the string *abcbc*, the suffix *bc* is also a prefix of the suffix *bcbc*.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] In such a case, the path spelling out *bc* will not end in a leaf, violating the fifth rule.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] To fix this problem, S is padded with a terminal symbol not seen in the string (usually denoted `$`).
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] This ensures that no suffix is a prefix of another, and that there will be n leaf nodes, one for each of the n suffixes of S .
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Since all internal non-root nodes are branching, there can be at most $n-1$ such nodes, and $n+(n-1)+1=2n$ nodes in total ( n leaves, $n-1$ internal non-root nodes, 1 root).
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] A generalized suffix tree is a suffix tree made for a set of strings instead of a single string.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] It represents all suffixes from this set of strings.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Each string must be terminated by a different termination symbol.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] A suffix tree for a string S of length n can be built in $\Theta (n)$ time, if the letters come from an alphabet of integers in a polynomial range (in particular, this is true for constant-sized alphabets).
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] For larger alphabets, the running time is dominated by first sorting the letters to bring them into a range of size $O(n)$ ; in general, this takes $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The costs below are given under the assumption that the alphabet is constant.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Assume that a suffix tree has been built for the string S of length n , or that a generalised suffix tree has been built for the set of strings $D=\{S_{1},S_{2},\dots ,S_{K}\}$ of total length $n=n_{1}+n_{2}+\cdots +n_{K}$ .
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The suffix tree can be prepared for constant time lowest common ancestor retrieval between nodes in $\Theta (n)$ time.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Suffix trees can be used to solve a large number of string problems that occur in text-editing, free-text search, computational biology and other application areas.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Suffix trees are often used in bioinformatics applications, searching for patterns in DNA or protein sequences (which can be viewed as long strings of characters).
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The ability to search efficiently with mismatches might be considered their greatest strength.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Suffix trees are also used in data compression; they can be used to find repeated data, and can be used for the sorting stage of the Burrows–Wheeler transform.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Variants of the LZW compression schemes use suffix trees (LZSS).
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] A suffix tree is also used in suffix tree clustering, a data clustering algorithm used in some search engines.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] If each node and edge can be represented in $\Theta (1)$ space, the entire tree can be represented in $\Theta (n)$ space.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The total length of all the strings on all of the edges in the tree is $O(n^{2})$ , but each edge can be stored as the position and length of a substring of S, giving a total space usage of $\Theta (n)$ computer words.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The worst-case space usage of a suffix tree is seen with a fibonacci word, giving the full $2n$ nodes.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] An important choice when making a suffix tree implementation is the parent-child relationships between nodes.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The most common is using linked lists called **sibling lists**.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Each node has a pointer to its first child, and to the next node in the child list it is a part of.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Other implementations with efficient running time properties use hash maps, sorted or unsorted arrays (with array doubling), or balanced search trees.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The insertion cost is amortised, and that the costs for hashing are given for perfect hashing.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The large amount of information in each edge and node makes the suffix tree very expensive, consuming about 10 to 20 times the memory size of the source text in good implementations.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Researchers have continued to find smaller indexing structures.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Various parallel algorithms to speed up suffix tree construction have been proposed.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Recently, a practical parallel algorithm for suffix tree construction with $O(n)$ work (sequential time) and $O(\log ^{2}n)$ span has been developed.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The algorithm achieves good parallel scalability on shared-memory multicore machines and can index the human genome – approximately 3GB – in under 3 minutes using a 40-core machine.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] Though linear, the memory usage of a suffix tree is significantly higher than the actual size of the sequence collection.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] For a large text, construction may require external memory approaches.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] There are theoretical results for constructing suffix trees in external memory.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The algorithm by Farach-Colton, Ferragina & Muthukrishnan (2000) is theoretically optimal, with an I/O complexity equal to that of sorting.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] However the overall intricacy of this algorithm has prevented, so far, its practical implementation.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] On the other hand, there have been practical works for constructing disk-based suffix trees which scale to (few) GB/hours.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The state of the art methods are TDD, TRELLIS, DiGeST, and B2ST.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] TDD and TRELLIS scale up to the entire human genome resulting in a disk-based suffix tree of a size in the tens of gigabytes.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] However, these methods cannot handle efficiently collections of sequences exceeding 3 GB.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] DiGeST performs significantly better and is able to handle collections of sequences in the order of 6 GB in about 6 hours.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] All these methods can efficiently build suffix trees for the case when the tree does not fit in main memory, but the input does.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] The most recent method, B2ST, scales to handle inputs that do not fit in main memory.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] ERA is a recent parallel suffix tree construction method that is significantly faster.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] ERA can index the entire human genome in 19 minutes on an 8-core desktop computer with 16 GB RAM.
[src:ternary-search-tree/suffix-tree] On a simple Linux cluster with 16 nodes (4 GB RAM per node), ERA can index the entire human genome in less than 9 minutes.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] In computer science, a **ternary search tree** is a type of trie (sometimes called a *prefix tree*) where nodes are arranged in a manner similar to a binary search tree, but with up to three children rather than the binary tree's limit of two.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Like other prefix trees, a ternary search tree can be used as an associative map structure with the ability for incremental string search.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] However, ternary search trees are more space efficient compared to standard prefix trees, at the cost of speed.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Common applications for ternary search trees include spell-checking and auto-completion.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] A node may also have a pointer to its parent node as well as an indicator as to whether or not the node marks the end of a word.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] The *lo kid* pointer must point to a node whose character value is *less than the current node*.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] The *hi kid* pointer must point to a node whose character is *greater than the current node*.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] The *equal kid* points to the next character in the word.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] As with other trie data structures, each node in a ternary search tree represents a prefix of the stored strings.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] All strings in the middle subtree of a node start with that prefix.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Inserting a value into a ternary search can be defined recursively or iteratively much as lookups are defined.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] This recursive method is continually called on nodes of the tree given a key which gets progressively shorter by pruning characters off the front of the key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] If this method reaches a node that has not been created, it creates the node and assigns it the character value of the first character in the key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Whether a new node is created or not, the method checks to see if the first character in the string is greater than or less than the character value in the node and makes a recursive call on the appropriate node as in the lookup operation.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] If, however, the key's first character is equal to the node's value then the insertion procedure is called on the equal kid and the key's first character is pruned away.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Like binary search trees and other data structures, ternary search trees can become degenerate depending on the order of the keys.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Inserting keys in alphabetical order is one way to attain the worst possible degenerate tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Inserting the keys in random order often produces a well-balanced tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] To look up a particular node or the data associated with a node, a string key is needed.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] A lookup procedure begins by checking the root node of the tree and determining which of the following conditions has occurred.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] If the first character of the string is less than the character in the root node, a recursive lookup can be called on the tree whose root is the lo kid of the current root.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Similarly, if the first character is greater than the current node in the tree, then a recursive call can be made to the tree whose root is the hi kid of the current node.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] As a final case, if the first character of the string is equal to the character of the current node then the function returns the node if there are no more characters in the key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] If there are more characters in the key then the first character of the key must be removed and a recursive call is made given the equal kid node and the modified key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] This can also be written in a non-recursive way by using a pointer to the current node and a pointer to the current character of the key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] The delete operation consists of searching for a key string in the search tree and finding a node, called firstMid in the below pseudocode, such that the path from the middle child of firstMid to the end of the search path for the key string has no left or right children.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] This would represent a unique suffix in the ternary tree corresponding to the key string.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] If there is no such path, this means that the key string is either fully contained as a prefix of another string, or is not in the search tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Many implementations make use of an end of string character to ensure only the latter case occurs.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] The path is then deleted from firstMid.mid to the end of the search path.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] In the case that firstMid is the root, the key string must have been the last string in the tree, and thus the root is set to null after the deletion.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] The running time of ternary search trees varies significantly with the input.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Ternary search trees run best when given several *similar strings*, especially when those strings *share a common prefix*.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Alternatively, ternary search trees are effective when storing a large number of relatively *short strings* (such as words in a dictionary).
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Running times for ternary search trees are similar to binary search trees, in that they typically run in logarithmic time, but can run in linear time in the degenerate (worst) case.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Further, the size of the strings must also be kept in mind when considering runtime.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] For example, in the search path for a string of length *k*, there will be *k* traversals down middle children in the tree, as well as a logarithmic number of traversals down left and right children in the tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Thus, in a ternary search tree on a small number of very large strings the lengths of the strings can dominate the runtime.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] While being slower than other prefix trees, ternary search trees can be better suited for larger data sets due to their space-efficiency.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Hashtables can also be used in place of ternary search trees for mapping strings to values.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] However, hash maps also frequently use more memory than ternary search trees (but not as much as tries).
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Additionally, hash maps are typically slower at reporting a string that is not in the same data structure, because it must compare the entire string rather than just the first few characters.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] There is some evidence that shows ternary search trees running faster than hash maps.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Additionally, hash maps do not allow for many of the uses of ternary search trees, such as *near-neighbor lookups*.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] If storing dictionary words is all that is required (i.e., storage of information auxiliary to each word is not required), a minimal deterministic acyclic finite state automaton (DAFSA) would use less space than a trie or a ternary search tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] This is because a DAFSA can compress identical branches from the trie which correspond to the same suffixes (or parts) of different words being stored.
[src:ternary-search-tree/ternary-search-tree] Ternary search trees can be used to solve many problems in which a large number of strings must be stored and retrieved in an arbitrary order.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] In computer science, a **trie** (/ˈtraɪ/, /ˈtriː/ ⓘ), also known as a **digital tree** or **prefix tree**, is a specialized search tree data structure used to store and retrieve strings from a dictionary or set.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Unlike a binary search tree, nodes in a trie do not store their associated key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Instead, each node's *position* within the trie determines its associated key, with the connections between nodes defined by individual characters rather than the entire key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Tries are particularly effective for tasks such as autocomplete, spell checking, and IP routing, offering advantages over hash tables due to their prefix-based organization and lack of hash collisions.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Every child node shares a common prefix with its parent node, and the root node represents the empty string.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] While basic trie implementations can be memory-intensive, various optimization techniques such as compression and bitwise representations have been developed to improve their efficiency.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] A notable optimization is the radix tree, which provides more efficient prefix-based storage.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] While tries store character strings, they can be adapted to work with any ordered sequence of elements, such as permutations of digits or shapes.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] A notable variant is the **bitwise trie**, which uses individual bits from fixed-length binary data (such as integers or memory addresses) as keys.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] The idea of a trie for representing a set of strings was first abstractly described by Axel Thue in 1912.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Tries were first described in a computer context by René de la Briandais in 1959.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] The idea was independently described in 1960 by Edward Fredkin, who coined the term *trie*, pronouncing it /ˈtriː/ (as "tree"), after the middle syllable of *retrieval*.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] However, other authors pronounce it /ˈtraɪ/ (as "try"), in an attempt to distinguish it verbally from "tree".
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Tries are a form of string-indexed look-up data structure, which is used to store a dictionary list of words that can be searched on in a manner that allows for efficient generation of completion lists.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] A prefix trie is an ordered tree data structure used in the representation of a set of strings over a finite alphabet set, which allows efficient storage of words with common prefixes.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Tries can be efficacious on string-searching algorithms such as predictive text, approximate string matching, and spell checking in comparison to binary search trees.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] A trie can be seen as a tree-shaped deterministic finite automaton.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Tries support various operations: insertion, deletion, and lookup of a string key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Tries are composed of nodes that contain links, which either point to other suffix child nodes or *null*.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] As for every tree, each node except the root is pointed to by only one other node, called its *parent*.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Each node contains as many links as the number of characters in the applicable alphabet (although tries tend to have a substantial number of null links).
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] In some cases, the alphabet used is simply that of the character encoding—resulting in, for example, a size of 128 in the case of ASCII.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Each node contains one possible link to a prefix of strong keys of the set.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] A basic structure type of nodes in the trie is as follows: ${\text{Node}}$ may contain an optional ${\text{Value}}$ , which is associated with the key that corresponds to the node.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Searching for a value in a trie is guided by the characters in the search string key, as each node in the trie contains a corresponding link to each possible character in the given string.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Thus, following the string within the trie yields the associated value for the given string key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] A null link during the search indicates the inexistence of the key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] The following pseudocode implements the search procedure for a given string key in a rooted trie x.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] In the above pseudocode, x and key correspond to the pointer of the trie's root node and the string key, respectively.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] The search operation takes $O(m)$ time, where m is the size of the string parameter key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] In a balanced binary search tree, on the other hand, it takes $O(m\log n)$ time, in the worst case, since key needs to be compared with $O(\log n)$ other keys and each comparison takes $O(m)$ time, in the worst case.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] The trie occupies less space, in comparison with a binary search tree, in the case of a large number of short strings, since nodes share common initial string subsequences and store the keys implicitly.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Insertion into a trie is guided by using the character sets as indexes to the children array until the last character of the string key is reached.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Each node in the trie corresponds to one call of the radix sorting routine, as the trie structure reflects the execution pattern of the top-down radix sort.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] If null links are encountered before reaching the last character of the string key, new nodes are created.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] The input value is assigned to the value of the last node traversed, which is the node that corresponds to the key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Deletion of a key–value pair from a trie involves finding the node corresponding to the key, setting its value to null, and recursively removing nodes that have no children.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] The procedure begins by examining key; an empty string indicates arrival at the node corresponding to the (original) key, in which case its value is set to null.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] If the node, then, has null value and no children, it is removed from the trie by returning null; otherwise, the node is kept by returning the node itself.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] However, tries are less efficient than a hash table when the data is directly accessed on a secondary storage device such as a hard disk drive that has higher random access time than the main memory.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Tries can be represented in several ways, corresponding to different trade-offs between memory use and speed of the operations.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Using a vector of pointers for representing a trie consumes enormous space; however, memory space can be reduced at the expense of running time if a singly linked list is used for each node vector, as most entries of the vector contains ${\text{nil}}$ .
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Techniques such as *alphabet reduction* may reduce the large space requirements by reinterpreting the original string as a longer string over a smaller alphabet.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] For example, a string of n bytes can alternatively be regarded as a string of 2*n* four-bit units.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] This can reduce memory usage by a factor of eight; but lookups need to visit twice as many nodes in the worst case.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Another technique includes storing a vector of 256 ASCII pointers as a bitmap of 256 bits representing ASCII alphabet, which reduces the size of individual nodes dramatically.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Bitwise tries are used to address the enormous space requirement for the trie nodes in a naive simple pointer vector implementations.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Each character in the string key set is represented via individual bits, which are used to traverse the trie over a string key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] The implementations for these types of trie use vectorized CPU instructions to find the first set bit in a fixed-length key input (e.g.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] GCC's `__builtin_clz()` intrinsic function).
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Accordingly, the set bit is used to index the first item, or child node, in the 32- or 64-entry based bitwise tree.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Search then proceeds by testing each subsequent bit in the key.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] This procedure is also cache-local and highly parallelizable due to register independency, and thus performant on out-of-order execution CPUs.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Radix tree, also known as a **compressed trie**, is a space-optimized variant of a trie in which any node with only one child gets merged with its parent; elimination of branches of the nodes with a single child results in better metrics in both space and time.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] This works best when the trie remains static and set of keys stored are very sparse within their representation space.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] One more approach for static tries is to "pack" the trie by storing disjoint sets of children in the same memory location, interleaved.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Patricia trees are a particular implementation of the compressed binary trie that uses the binary encoding of the string keys in its representation.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Every node in a Patricia tree contains an index, known as a "skip number", that stores the node's branching index to avoid empty subtrees during traversal.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] A naive implementation of a trie consumes immense storage due to larger number of leaf-nodes caused by the sparse distribution of keys; Patricia trees can be efficient for such cases.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] A representation of a Patricia tree is shown to the right.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Each index value adjacent to the nodes represents the "skip number"—the index of the bit with which branching is to be decided.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] The skip number 1 at node 0 corresponds to the position 1 in the binary encoded ASCII where the leftmost bit differed in the key set X.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] The skip number is crucial for search, insertion, and deletion of nodes in the Patricia tree, and a bit masking operation is performed during every iteration.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Trie data structures are commonly used in predictive text or autocomplete dictionaries, and approximate matching algorithms.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Tries enable faster searches, occupy less space, especially when the set contains large number of short strings, thus used in spell checking, hyphenation applications and longest prefix match algorithms.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] However, if storing dictionary words is all that is required (i.e. there is no need to store metadata associated with each word), a minimal deterministic acyclic finite state automaton (DAFSA) or radix tree would use less storage space than a trie.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] This is because DAFSAs and radix trees can compress identical branches from the trie that correspond to the same suffixes (or parts) of different words being stored.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] String dictionaries are also utilized in natural language processing, such as finding lexicon of a text corpus.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Lexicographic sorting of a set of string keys can be implemented by building a trie for the given keys and traversing the tree in pre-order fashion; this is also a form of radix sort.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Tries are also fundamental data structures for burstsort, which is notable for being the fastest string sorting algorithm as of 2007, accomplished by its efficient use of CPU cache.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] A special kind of trie, called a suffix tree, can be used to index all suffixes in a text to carry out fast full-text searches.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] A specialized kind of trie called a compressed trie, is used in web search engines for storing the indexes - a collection of all searchable words.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Each terminal node is associated with a list of URLs—called occurrence list—to pages that match the keyword.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] The trie is stored in the main memory, whereas the occurrence is kept in an external storage, frequently in large clusters, or the in-memory index points to documents stored in an external location.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Tries are used in Bioinformatics, notably in sequence alignment software applications such as BLAST, which indexes all the different substrings of length *k* (called k-mers) of a text by storing the positions of their occurrences in a compressed trie sequence databases.
[src:ternary-search-tree/trie] Compressed variants of tries, such as databases for managing Forwarding Information Base (FIB), are used in storing IP address prefixes within routers and bridges for prefix-based lookup to resolve mask-based operations in IP routing.
